## M22.1(3/8): `for *x in v` (by-reference loop binding) is reserved in V1.
##
## Per GPT-5.5 entry 39 (M22.1 "fake-surface audit"): the M20i.1
## grammar accepted `for *x in v` as a "pointer/slot iteration"
## mode, but for Copy Vec elements the emit was IDENTICAL to bare
## `for x in v` (the `*` was silently ignored). That's the
## fake-surface hazard — a sigil in the surface with no enforced
## semantics. Resource Vec already rejected `*` mode at sema, so
## V1 now rejects it everywhere.
##
## V1 has one iteration spelling per element kind:
##   - Copy Vec:     `for x in v`        # bare value iteration
##   - Resource Vec: `for x in ?v`       # read-borrow over each slot
##
## If by-reference iteration returns in a future arc, the Rig-
## native spelling is more likely borrow-shaped (`for ?x in v` /
## `for !x in v`) than pointer-shaped — `*x` already means shared
## ownership in the rest of the sigil grid, so reusing it here
## would muddy the algebra.

sub main()
  v: Vec(Int) = Vec()
  (!v).push(1)
  for *x in v        # error: by-reference loop binding reserved
    print(x)
